# 🔬 Automated Gram-Stain Image Interpretation
### YOLOv8 Bacterial Detection • BLIP-2 Caption Generation • CLIP/Rule-Based Caption Evaluation

> An end-to-end deep learning pipeline for automated interpretation of Gram-stained microscopic images using object detection, vision-language models, and quantitative caption evaluation.

---

## 📌 Overview

Manual interpretation of Gram-stained microscopic images is a fundamental yet time-consuming task in microbiology laboratories. It requires trained personnel to accurately identify bacterial morphology, Gram reaction, staining characteristics, and organism distribution.

This project presents an automated AI-assisted workflow that combines:

- **YOLOv8** for bacterial detection and classification
- **BLIP-2 (Flan-T5-XL)** for structured microbiology caption generation
- **Rule-based and CLIP-based evaluation** for quantitative assessment of generated captions

The system produces standardized microbiological descriptions supported by detection statistics while minimizing hallucinations through prompt engineering and post-generation validation.

> **Note:** This project is intended for research and educational purposes only and is **not designed for clinical diagnosis.**

---

# 🚀 Features

- Custom-trained YOLOv8 bacterial detector
- Detection of four Gram-stain bacterial categories
- Automatic counting and percentage calculation
- Mean confidence estimation
- Bounding-box visualization
- Structured microbiology report generation
- Prompt-constrained BLIP-2 captioning
- Rule-based microbiology validation
- CLIP-based semantic evaluation
- Batch processing of Gram-stain images
- CSV report generation

---

# 🎯 Research Objective

Conventional Gram-stain interpretation requires expert examination of:

- Gram reaction
- Cellular morphology
- Smear characteristics
- Stain color consistency
- Relative abundance of bacterial populations

The objective of this project is to automate this workflow using deep learning by generating structured, evidence-supported microbiological descriptions from digital Gram-stain images.

---

